data.content:
Here's what happened and how to fix it:

## The Problem

In C# 14 / .NET 10, new **span overload resolution** rules cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. `MemoryExtensions.Contains` is not representable in a LINQ expression tree, so it throws at runtime.

## The Fix

Force the call to resolve to `Enumerable.Contains` by any of these approaches:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three prevent the compiler from choosing the span-based overload.
